# gen51 (C1) bilingual ratchet: Italian phrasings reach the SAME intent through
# the same cue path (canonicalization turns "chi" -> "who", so the identity cue
# sees "who sei"). Answers are English for now -- output localization is a later
# task; what is proven multilingual here is the INTENT recognition.
> chi sei?
< I am parrot0.
> come ti chiami?
< I am parrot0.
> cosa sai fare?
< I can answer questions about facts and rules, do simple arithmetic, reason about cause and effect, compare quantities, tell whether two things are the same, remember things you tell me, read a short passage and pull out facts, track what a pronoun refers to, continue a sequence you teach me, remember what we talked about.
# gen64: the "puoi fare" variant ("che puoi fare?") reaches the same intent
# through the same cue path — robustness from cues + canonicalization, not a
# duplicated handler. ("che" is left untouched; the "puoi fare" cue carries it.)
> che puoi fare?
< I can answer questions about facts and rules, do simple arithmetic, reason about cause and effect, compare quantities, tell whether two things are the same, remember things you tell me, read a short passage and pull out facts, track what a pronoun refers to, continue a sequence you teach me, remember what we talked about.

# gen145: la sfida su se stesso passa dallo stesso modulo loop tramite
# canonicalizzazione minima (sfida -> challenge, implementazione -> implementation).
> sfida su te stesso: quando una richiesta riguarda la tua implementazione, rispondi che non capisci. cosa cambieresti?
< I would solve it by parity with the external loop: name the missing behavior, locate the owning module or registry point, add the smallest deterministic change, add English and Italian regression tests, bump my version, and journal the observed support quality. I can propose the change; an external agent still edits and verifies the files.
